<subSubSection id="C36BB9A4BB5BFFADFF1845DCFB24F836" box="[198,1267,1923,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BCEEA2FBB5BFFADFF1845DCFB24F836" blockId="7.[151,1436,1923,2029]" box="[198,1267,1923,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB5BFFADFF1845DCFEB0F836" bold="true" box="[198,359,1923,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Distribution.</emphasis>
Only known from the 
<typeStatus id="54CA548DBB5BFFADFDAC45DCFD73F836" box="[626,676,1923,1949]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">type</typeStatus>
locality: Caraguez Bay, 
<collectingCountry id="F366AABFBB5BFFADFC1B45DCFBF1F836" box="[965,1062,1923,1949]" name="Ecuador" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation id="C6F3DF94BB5BFFADFBEB45DCFB47F836" box="[1077,1168,1923,1949]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="10.[151,241,780,804]" captionText="TABLE 2. Geographical distribution of the eastern Pacific species of Leptogorgia Milne Edwards &amp; Haime, 1857. Country of the type locality is marked in bold." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Table 2</tableCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="134AF6AABB5BFFADFB4345DCFB34F836" box="[1181,1251,1923,1949]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1519,1543]" captionTargetBox="[393,1194,394,1494]" captionTargetId="figure-288@8.[393,1194,394,1494]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Geographical distribution of Leptogorgia aequatorialis and Leptogorgia obscura." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB9A4BB5BFFA2FF1845F4FB13F86B" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BCEEA2FBB5BFFA2FF1845F4FDB3FEF9" blockId="7.[151,1436,1923,2029]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,152,338]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB5BFFADFF1845F4FEE8F86E" bold="true" box="[198,319,1963,1989]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks.</emphasis>
Bielschowsky (1918, 1929) made a revision of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB5BFFADFC7945F4FBEEF86E" authorityName="Lamouroux" authorityYear="1812" box="[935,1081,1963,1989]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Gorgoniidae</taxonomicName>
overlooking early type designations which in some cases affected concepts of nomenclature. These were later revised and emended by Bayer (1951). Bielschowsky (1918, 1929) described six new species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FC0142C7FBB9FF1A" authorityName="Milne Edwards &amp; Haime" authorityYear="1857" box="[991,1134,152,177]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FC0142C7FBB9FF1A" box="[991,1134,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Leptogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from various localities in the eastern Pacific without designating 
<typeStatus id="54CA548DBB54FFA2FDBC429FFD0FFF71" box="[610,728,192,218]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">holotypes</typeStatus>
. Herein we consider valid only three of them; 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FB2D429FFF64FEAA" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1918" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="aequatorialis">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FB2D429FFF64FEAA" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. aequatorialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FF1C42B7FE97FEAA" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[194,320,232,257]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FF1C42B7FE97FEAA" box="[194,320,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FEA542B7FD00FEA9" authority="Bielschowsky, 1929" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[379,727,232,258]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FEA542B7FE08FEAA" box="[379,479,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. parva</emphasis>
Bielschowsky, 1929
</taxonomicName>
, and have synonymized the other three species (see below). Of the material Bielschowsky examined, only a fragment of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FCB3434FFBFDFE82" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1918" box="[877,1066,272,297]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="aequatorialis">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FCB3434FFBFDFE82" box="[877,1066,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. aequatorialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, two colonies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FB22434FFAB6FE82" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[1276,1377,272,297]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FB22434FFAB6FE82" box="[1276,1377,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and one small colony of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FE584367FDD4FEFA" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[390,515,312,337]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FE584367FDD4FEFA" box="[390,515,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remain.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF0EBAA7BB54FFA2FF4947B0FB5AF9AC" box="[151,1165,1519,1543]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" startId="8.[151,255,1519,1543]" targetBox="[393,1194,394,1494]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph id="8BCEEA2FBB54FFA2FF4947B0FB5AF9AC" blockId="8.[151,1165,1519,1543]" box="[151,1165,1519,1543]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FF4947B0FEF7F9AC" bold="true" box="[151,288,1519,1543]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">FIGURE 3.</emphasis>
Geographical distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FD8547AFFCA5F9AC" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1918" box="[603,882,1520,1543]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="aequatorialis">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FD8547AFFCA5F9AC" box="[603,882,1520,1543]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Leptogorgia aequatorialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FC7847AFFB51F9AC" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[934,1158,1520,1543]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FC7847AFFB51F9AC" box="[934,1158,1520,1543]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Leptogorgia obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BCEEA2FBB54FFA2FF184461FB13F86B" blockId="8.[151,1436,1598,1984]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
These three species are similar in the style of branching (irregular pinnate), the prominent polyp-mounds, and also the size of the known specimens is similar, but they differ in the colour of the colonies, the colour of the sclerites and the sclerite composition. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FD5F44D1FC63F90C" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1918" box="[641,948,1678,1703]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="aequatorialis">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FD5F44D1FC63F90C" box="[641,948,1678,1703]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Leptogorgia aequatorialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is of a distinct deep bright orange colour, with orange coenenchymal sclerites, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FD8F44E9FD07F964" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[593,720,1718,1743]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FD8F44E9FD07F964" box="[593,720,1718,1743]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is dark violet, with violet and pink coenenchymal sclerites, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FF164481FEFCF95C" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[200,299,1758,1783]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FF164481FEFCF95C" box="[200,299,1758,1783]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is purplish red, with red, pink and yellow coenenchymal sclerites (all of these specimens are preserved in ethanol); the spindles in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FDF84559FD36F8B4" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1918" box="[550,737,1798,1823]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="aequatorialis">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FDF84559FD36F8B4" box="[550,737,1798,1823]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. aequatorialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are smaller than in the other two species. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FB374559FA9BF8B4" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[1257,1356,1798,1823]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FB374559FA9BF8B4" box="[1257,1356,1798,1823]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FA5A4559FF22F8EC" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FA5A4559FF22F8EC" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the longest spindles reach 
<quantity id="4C8947CABB54FFA2FD9E4571FD79F8E3" box="[576,686,1838,1864]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="0.12">0.12 mm</quantity>
, but the occurrence of spindles with acute ends in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FAC64571FAA9F8EC" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[1304,1406,1838,1863]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FAC64571FAA9F8EC" box="[1304,1406,1838,1863]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is higher than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FE9F4509FE6AF8C4" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[321,445,1878,1903]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FE9F4509FE6AF8C4" box="[321,445,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation id="C6F3DF94BB54FFA2FE134509FDF2F8DB" box="[461,549,1878,1904]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,241,155,179]" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparative characteristics of the eastern Pacific species of Leptogorgia Milne Edwards &amp; Haime, 1857." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Table 1</tableCitation>
). The small (up to 
<quantity id="4C8947CABB54FFA2FCDB4509FCB8F8DB" box="[773,879,1878,1904]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="0.04">0.04 mm</quantity>
) biscuit-like anthocodial rods of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FB2D4509FF64F83C" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1918" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="aequatorialis">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FB2D4509FF64F83C" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. aequatorialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differentiate this species from the other two. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FD254521FCB7F83C" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[763,864,1918,1943]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FD254521FCB7F83C" box="[763,864,1918,1943]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
anthocodial rods are orange and measure up to 
<quantity id="4C8947CABB54FFA2FF4945F9FED5F86B" box="[151,258,1958,1984]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7191ACBB54FFA2FEF245F9FE7EF814" authorityName="Bielschowsky" authorityYear="1929" box="[300,425,1958,1983]" class="Anthozoa" family="Gorgoniidae" genus="Leptogorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="obscura">
<emphasis id="B905363DBB54FFA2FEF245F9FE7EF814" box="[300,425,1958,1983]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">L. obscura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are pale orange, amber, and pink, and measure up to 
<quantity id="4C8947CABB54FFA2FB8A45F9FB17F86B" box="[1108,1216,1958,1984]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="0.06">0.06 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
